"Bekryaev R.V., Polyakov I.V., Alexeev V.A.","Role of polar amplification in long-term surface air temperature variations and modern arctic warming",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","14",,"3888","3906",,,10.1175/2010JCLI3297.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956909974&partnerID=40&md5=ad4e91232e8305f8f84033b3293b268d","Voeikov Main Geophysical Observatory, St. Petersburg State University, St. Petersburg, Russian Federation; International Arctic Research Center, University of Alaska Fairbanks, Fairbanks, AK, United States","Bekryaev, R.V., Voeikov Main Geophysical Observatory, St. Petersburg State University, St. Petersburg, Russian Federation; Polyakov, I.V., International Arctic Research Center, University of Alaska Fairbanks, Fairbanks, AK, United States; Alexeev, V.A., International Arctic Research Center, University of Alaska Fairbanks, Fairbanks, AK, United States","This study uses an extensive dataset of monthly surface air temperature (SAT) records (including previously unutilized) from high-latitude (&gt;60°N) meteorological land stations. Most records have been updated by very recent observations (up to December 2008). Using these data, a high-latitude warming rate of 1.36°C century -1 is documented for 1875-2008-the trend is almost 2 times stronger than the Northern Hemisphere trend (0.79°C century -1), with an accelerated warming rate in the most recent decade (1.35°C decade -1). Stronger warming in high-latitude regions is a manifestation of polar amplification (PA). Changes in SAT suggest two spatial scales of PA-hemispheric and local. A new stable statistical measure of PA linking high-latitude and hemispheric temperature anomalies via a regression relationship is proposed. For 1875-2008, this measure yields PA of ~1.62. Local PA related to the ice-albedo feedback mechanisms is autumnal and coastal, extending several hundred kilometers inland. Heat budget estimates suggest that a recent reduction of arctic ice and anomalously high SATs cannot be explained by ice-albedo feedback mechanisms alone, and the role of large-scale mechanisms of PA of global warming should not be overlooked. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Arctic ice; Arctic warming; Data sets; Feedback mechanisms; Heat budget; High-latitude regions; Land stations; Northern Hemispheres; Regression relationship; Spatial scale; Statistical measures; Surface air temperatures; Temperature anomaly; Amplification; Atmospheric temperature; Flight dynamics; Global warming; Solar radiation; Ice; air temperature; albedo; arctic environment; feedback mechanism; global warming; heat budget; Northern Hemisphere; temperature anomaly",,,,,,"(2005) Arctic Climate Impact Assessment, p. 1042. , ACIA, Cambridge University Press; Alexeev, V.A., Sensitivity to CO 2 doubling of an atmospheric GCM coupled to an oceanic mixed layer: A linear analysis (2003) Climate Dyn., 20, pp. 775-787; Alexeev, V.A., Langen, P.L., Bates, J.R., Polar amplification of surface warming on an aquaplanet in ghost forcing experiments without sea ice feedbacks (2005) Climate Dyn., 24, pp. 655-666. , doi:10.1007/s00382-005-0018-3; Belchansky, G.I., Douglas, D.C., Platonov, N.G., Fluctuating Arctic sea ice thickness changes estimated by an in situ learned and empirically forced neural network model (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 716-729; Bloomfield, P., Trends in global temperature (1992) Climatic Change, 21, pp. 1-16; Bloomfield, P., Nychka, D., Climate spectra and detecting climate change (1992) Climatic Change, 21, pp. 275-287; Bony, S., How well do we understand and evaluate climate change feedback processes? (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 3445-3482; Brillinger, D.R., (1981) Time Series: Data Analysis and Theory, p. 540. , Holden Day; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new data set from 1850 (2006) J. Geophys. Res., 111, pp. D12106. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006548; (1954) Karelo-Finskaya SSR: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 2, p. 185. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR, Hydrometeoizdat; (1954) Leningrad, Pskov, and Novgorod Regions: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 3, p. 346. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; (1954) Estonia SSR: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 4, p. 608. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; (1954) Molotov, Sverdlovsk, Cheliabinsk, Kurgan Regions, and Bashkir ASSR: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 9 A, p. 513. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; (1956) Murmansk and Archangel Regions and Komi ASSR: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 1, p. 563. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; (1957) Krasnoyarsky Krai: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Part I: Air Temperature, 21, p. 217. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; (1962) Vologodsky Region: Meteorological Data for Selected Years, Parts I-VIII: Air Temperature, Precipitation, Snow Cover, Wind, Humidity, Cloudiness, Sunshine, Soil Temperature, Fogs, Thunderstorms, Blizzards, Air Pressure, Hail, 1, p. 600. , Climatologic Reference Book of the USSR. Hydrometeoizdat; Comiso, J.C., Parkinson, C.L., Gersten, R., Stock, L., Accelerated decline in the Arctic sea ice cover (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L01703. , doi:10.1029/2007GL031972; Cramer, H., (1999) Mathematical Methods of Statistics, p. 575. , 19th ed. Princeton University Press; Dery, S.J., Brown, R.D., Recent Northern Hemisphere snow cover extent trends and implications for the snow-albedo feedback (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L22504. , doi:10.1029/2007GL031474; Deser, C., Tomas, R., Alexander, M., Lawrence, D., The seasonal atmospheric response to projected Arctic sea ice loss in the late twenty-first century (2010) J. Climat